# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aslwrite
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aslwrite/1829-braille] Louis Braille's original publication, *Procedure for Writing Words, Music, and Plainsong in Dots* (1829), credits Barbier's night writing as being the basis for the braille script.
[src:aslwrite/1829-braille] It differed in a fundamental way from modern braille: It contained nine decades (series) of characters rather than the modern five, utilizing dashes as well as dots.
[src:aslwrite/1829-braille] Braille recognized, however, that the dashes were problematic, being difficult to distinguish from the dots in practice, and those characters were abandoned in the second edition of the book.
[src:aslwrite/1829-braille] The first four decades indicated the 40 letters of the alphabet (39 letters of the French alphabet, plus English *w*); the fifth the digits; the sixth punctuation; and the seventh and part of the eighth mathematical symbols.
[src:aslwrite/1829-braille] The seventh decade was also used for musical notes.
[src:aslwrite/1829-braille] Most of the remaining characters were unassigned.
[src:aslwrite/1829-braille] Thus the 1st and 5th decades occupied only the top half of the cell, while all characters in the other decades had a dot or dash in the bottom row.
[src:aslwrite/1829-braille] The supplemental signs were ⠄⠤⠜⠼ and a top dash with ⠠⠰.
[src:aslwrite/1829-braille] Of the 125 (53) possible patterns, 97 were used.
[src:aslwrite/1829-braille] The modern 5th decade and other supplemental signs do not appear in the 1829 version of braille, apart from ⠐ and ⠒ in plainsong notation.
[src:aslwrite/1829-braille] Anticipating that the dashes might prove problematic, Braille provided that the supplemental sign ⠼ (now known as the number sign) would shift the decade by four.
[src:aslwrite/1829-braille] That is, adding it to the first four decades would produce substitutes for the fifth through eighth.
[src:aslwrite/1829-braille] Only its use to replace the old fifth decade has been retained; the old sixth decade survives as the modern fifth, with the dash removed and the dots shifted down to replace it.
[src:aslwrite/1829-braille] The book allots a great deal of space to the representation of music.
[src:aslwrite/1829-braille] Instrumental notation was largely a one-to-one transcription of the system already in use for the blind.
[src:aslwrite/1829-braille] The durations of the notes and the accidentals, however, had to be replaced; for these the 7th decade was used, as shown in the table above.
[src:aslwrite/1829-braille] A simplified system for plainsong was provided.
[src:aslwrite/1829-braille] The twelve notes are the twelve characters of the upper half of the cell (the first and fifth decades) which do not have dashes.
[src:aslwrite/1829-braille] By themselves (1st decade), they indicate half notes.
[src:aslwrite/1829-braille] Quarter notes are 2nd decade, dotted quarter notes 3rd, and eighth notes 4th.
[src:aslwrite/1829-braille] Dotted half notes are indicated by a dash below (6th decade), whole notes by a dash above (7th decade), and dotted whole notes by a mid dash (8th decade).
[src:aslwrite/1829-braille] The alto, bass, treble, and tenor clefs were indicated by the 5th–8th characters of the fifth decade. ⠐ is the sharp-note prefix, ⠒ the bass-note prefix, and the equivalent with a dash the natural prefix. ⠄⠤ are the repetition sign and 'star'.
[src:aslwrite/1829-braille] The book finishes with a proposal for braille shorthand, utilizing the first decade for vowels, and the fifth for consonants (without a voicing distinction).
[src:aslwrite/1829-braille] That is, Braille's shorthand used a 4-dot cell rather than the standard 6-dot cell, taking two-thirds the space of normal braille, and one-third the space of Barbier's night writing.
[src:aslwrite/1829-braille] In the classroom, Braille's students found the characters with dashes to be impractical, as the dashes were not easily distinguishable from pairs of dots, and they were quickly abandoned.
[src:aslwrite/1829-braille] The second edition of the *Procédé*, published in 1837, sets out French Braille essentially as we know it today.
[src:aslwrite/1829-braille] According to Henri (1952), at right, the numerical sign was used with the new fifth decade, plus one of the supplementary characters, for mathematical notation: ⠼⠖ +, ⠼⠤ −, ⠼⠦ ×, ⠼⠲ /, ⠼⠶ =, ⠼⠜ √.
[src:aslwrite/1829-braille] Several of these values continue today in Antoine notation.
[src:aslwrite/1829-braille] The official Unicode encoding for Braille only specifies codepoints for modern dot-only patterns.
[src:aslwrite/1829-braille] An unofficial encoding for dash patterns can be found in the Under-ConScript Unicode Registry, and as such may be found in some fonts that cover characters from that agreement.
[src:aslwrite/1829-braille] Together, these two blocks can represent all cell definitions from the 1829 Braille specification.
[src:aslwrite/abjad-numerals] The **Abjad numerals**, also called **Hisab al-Jummal** (Arabic: حِسَاب ٱلْجُمَّل, *ḥisāb al-jummal*), are a decimal alphabetic numeral system/alphanumeric code, in which the 28 letters of the Arabic alphabet are assigned numerical values.
[src:aslwrite/abjad-numerals] They have been used in the Arabic-speaking world since before the eighth century when positional Arabic numerals were adopted.
[src:aslwrite/abjad-numerals] In modern Arabic, the word **ʾabjadīyah** (أَبْجَدِيَّة) means 'alphabet' in general.
[src:aslwrite/abjad-numerals] In the Abjad system, the first letter of the Arabic alphabet, ʾalif, is used to represent 1; the second letter, bāʾ, 2, up to 9.
[src:aslwrite/abjad-numerals] Letters then represent the first nine intervals of 10s and those of the 100s: yāʾ for 10, kāf for 20, qāf for 100, ending with 1000.
[src:aslwrite/abjad-numerals] The word *ʾabjad* (أبجد) itself derives from the first four letters (A-B-G-D) of the Semitic alphabet, including the Aramaic alphabet, Hebrew alphabet, Phoenician alphabet, and other scripts for Semitic languages.
[src:aslwrite/abjad-numerals] These alphabets contained only 22 letters, stopping at taw, numerically equivalent to 400.
[src:aslwrite/abjad-numerals] The Arabic Abjad system continues at this point with letters not found in other alphabets: thāʾ = 500, khāʾ = 600, dhāl = 700, etc.
[src:aslwrite/abjad-numerals] Abjad numerals in Arabic are similar to the alphanumeric codes of Hebrew gematria and Greek isopsephy.
[src:aslwrite/abjad-numerals] The Abjad order of the Arabic alphabet has two slightly different variants.
[src:aslwrite/abjad-numerals] The Arabic abjad order is not a simple historical continuation of the earlier north Semitic alphabetic order, since it has a position corresponding to the Aramaic letter *samekh / semkat* ס, yet no letter of the Arabic alphabet historically derives from that letter.
[src:aslwrite/abjad-numerals] In the most common Mashriqi abjad sequence, loss of **samekh** was compensated for by the split of **shin** ש into two independent Arabic letters, ش (**shīn**) and ﺱ (**sīn**), which moved up to take the place of **samekh**.
[src:aslwrite/abjad-numerals] In the Maghrebian abjad sequence (quoted in apparently earliest authorities and considered older), loss of **samekh** was compensated for by the split of **tsade** צ into two independent Arabic letters, ض (**ḍad**) and ص (**ṣad**), which moved up to take the place of **samekh**.
[src:aslwrite/abjad-numerals] Modern dictionaries and other reference books use the newer **hijāʾī** (هجائي) / **alifbāʾī** (أَلِفْبَائِي) and more common order, which partially groups letters together by similarity of shape, and is never used as numerals.
[src:aslwrite/abjad-numerals] Persian uses a slightly different order, in which و comes before ه instead of after it.
[src:aslwrite/abjad-numerals] Before the Hindu–Arabic numeral system, the abjad as numbers were used for all mathematical purposes.
[src:aslwrite/abjad-numerals] In modern Arabic, they are primarily used for numbering outlines, items in lists, and points of information.
[src:aslwrite/abjad-numerals] Equivalent to English, "A.", "B.", and "C." (or, rarer, Roman numerals: I, II, III, IV), in Arabic, thus "أ", then "ب", then "ج", not the first three letters of the modern **hijāʼī** order.
[src:aslwrite/abjad-numerals] Like Roman numerals, there is no representation of zero and there are no fractions.
[src:aslwrite/abjad-numerals] By convention, the numbers are written largest first (larger to smaller, going right to left).
[src:aslwrite/abjad-numerals] Reversing the order indicates multiplication, so for example بغ is 2000 while غب is 1002.
[src:aslwrite/abjad-numerals] (Contrast this with Roman numerals, where reversing the order indicates subtraction, e.g.
[src:aslwrite/abjad-numerals] The abjad numbers are also used to assign numerical values to Arabic words for purposes of numerology.
[src:aslwrite/abjad-numerals] The common Islamic phrase بسم الله الرحمن الرحيم **bismillāh al-Raḥmān al-Raḥīm** ('In the name of Allah, the most merciful, the most compassionate' – see Basmala) has a numeric value of 786 (from a letter-by-letter cumulative value of 2+60+40+1+30+30+5+1+30+200+8+40+50+1+30+200+8+10+40).
[src:aslwrite/abjad-numerals] The name Allāh الله by itself has the value 66 (1+30+30+5).
[src:aslwrite/abjad-numerals] Notice that some letters appear in their initial form and others in a *riqaa*-like form, with the *alif* having a different shape.
[src:aslwrite/abjad-numerals] The Abjad numerals are equivalent to the earlier Hebrew numerals up to 400.
[src:aslwrite/abjad-numerals] The Hebrew numeral system is known as Gematria and is used in Kabbalistic texts and numerology.
[src:aslwrite/abjad-numerals] Like the Abjad order, it is used in modern times for numbering outlines and points of information, including the first six days of the week.
[src:aslwrite/abjad-numerals] The Greek numerals differ in a number of ways from the Abjad ones (for instance in the Greek alphabet there is no equivalent for ص, **ṣād**).
[src:aslwrite/abjad-numerals] The Greek language system of letters-as-numbers is called isopsephy.
[src:aslwrite/abjad-numerals] In modern times the old 27-letter alphabet of this system also continues to be used for numbering lists.
[src:aslwrite/abjad] 'alphabet') is a writing system in which only consonants are represented by letter signs, leaving the vowels to be inferred by the reader (unless represented otherwise, such as by diacritics).
[src:aslwrite/abjad] This contrasts with alphabets that provide graphemes for both consonants and vowels.
[src:aslwrite/abjad] The term was introduced in 1990 by Peter T.
[src:aslwrite/abjad] Other terms for the same concept include **partial phonemic script**, **segmentally linear defective phonographic script**, **consonantary**, **consonant writing**, and **consonantal alphabet**.
[src:aslwrite/abjad] According to the formulations of Peter T.
[src:aslwrite/abjad] Daniels, abjads differ from alphabets in that only consonants, not vowels, are represented among the basic graphemes.
[src:aslwrite/abjad] Abjads differ from abugidas, another category defined by Daniels, in that in abjads, the vowel sound is *implied* by phonology, and where vowel marks exist for the system, such as niqqud for Hebrew and ḥarakāt for Arabic, their use is optional and not the dominant (or literate) form.
[src:aslwrite/abjad] Abugidas mark all vowels (other than the "inherent" vowel) with a diacritic, a minor attachment to the letter, a standalone grapheme, or (in Canadian Aboriginal syllabics) by rotation of the letter.
[src:aslwrite/abjad] Some abugidas use a special symbol to *suppress* the inherent vowel so that the consonant alone can be properly represented.
[src:aslwrite/abjad] In a syllabary, a grapheme denotes a complete syllable, that is, either a lone vowel sound or a combination of a vowel sound with one or more consonant sounds.
[src:aslwrite/abjad] The contrast of abjad versus alphabet has been rejected by other scholars because *abjad* is also used as a term for the Arabic numeral system.
[src:aslwrite/abjad] Also, it may be taken as suggesting that consonantal alphabets, in contrast to e.g. the Greek alphabet, were not yet true alphabets.
[src:aslwrite/abjad] Florian Coulmas, a critic of Daniels and of the abjad terminology, argues that this terminology can confuse alphabets with "transcription systems", and that there is no reason to relegate the Hebrew, Aramaic or Phoenician alphabets to second-class status as an "incomplete alphabet".
[src:aslwrite/abjad] However, Daniels's terminology has found acceptance in the linguistic community.
[src:aslwrite/abjad] The Proto-Sinaitic script represents the earliest-known example of alphabetic writing.
[src:aslwrite/abjad] The Proto-Sinaitic script is thought to represent, or at least indicate the existence of, an early ancestor of the many later Semitic consonantal scripts which continued to develop over time into more abstract, less visually representational forms, including the Phoenician abjad.
[src:aslwrite/abjad] The Phoenician abjad was a radical simplification of phonetic writing.
[src:aslwrite/abjad] Unlike other scripts, such as Mesopotamian cuneiform (logographic and syllabic) and Egyptian hieroglyphs (logographic and consonantal), the Phoenician abjad consisted of only a few dozen symbols.
[src:aslwrite/abjad] During these exchanges, the Phoenician script gave rise to a number of new writing systems, including the widely used Aramaic abjad and the Greek alphabet.
[src:aslwrite/abjad] The Greek alphabet was later developed into several alphabets, including Etruscan, Coptic, Cyrillic, and Latin (via Etruscan), while Aramaic became the ancestor of many abjads and abugidas of Asia, particularly in and around India, Southeast Asia, and Oceania.
[src:aslwrite/abjad] Impure abjads have characters for some vowels, optional vowel diacritics, or both.
[src:aslwrite/abjad] The term pure abjad refers to scripts entirely lacking in vowel indicators.
[src:aslwrite/abjad] This practice was at first rare and limited in scope but became increasingly common and more developed in later times.
[src:aslwrite/abjad] In the 9th century BC the Greeks adapted the Phoenician script for use in their own language.
[src:aslwrite/abjad] The phonetic structure of the Greek language created too many ambiguities when vowels went unrepresented, so the script was modified.
[src:aslwrite/abjad] They did not need letters for the guttural sounds represented by *aleph*, *he*, *heth* or *ayin*, so these symbols were assigned vocalic values.
[src:aslwrite/abjad] The letters *waw* and *yod* were also adapted into vowel signs; along with *he*, these were already used as *matres lectionis* in Phoenician.
[src:aslwrite/abjad] Abugidas developed along a slightly different route.
[src:aslwrite/abjad] The basic consonantal symbol was considered to have an inherent "a" vowel sound.
[src:aslwrite/abjad] Hooks or short lines attached to various parts of the basic letter modify the vowel.
[src:aslwrite/abjad] In this way, the South Arabian abjad evolved into the Geʽez script of Ethiopia between the 5th century BC and the 5th century AD.
[src:aslwrite/abjad] Similarly, the Brāhmī abugida of the Indian subcontinent developed around the 3rd century BC (from the Aramaic abjad, it has been hypothesized).
[src:aslwrite/abjad] The abjad form of writing is well-adapted to the morphological structure of the Semitic languages it was developed to write.
[src:aslwrite/abjad] This is because words in Semitic languages are formed from a root consisting of (usually) three consonants, the vowels being used to indicate inflectional or derived forms.
[src:aslwrite/abjad] In most cases, the absence of full glyphs for vowels makes the common root clearer, allowing readers to guess the meaning of unfamiliar words from familiar roots (especially in conjunction with context clues) and improving word recognition while reading for practiced readers.
[src:aslwrite/abjad] The Hebrew abjad has also been adapted to write Jewish languages like Ladino and Yiddish.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] This contrasts with a full alphabet, in which vowels have status equal to consonants, and with an abjad, in which vowel marking is absent, partial, or optional.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] In less formal contexts, all three types of script may be termed "alphabets".
[src:aslwrite/abugida] The terms also contrast them with a syllabary, in which a single symbol denotes the combination of a consonant and a vowel.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] Related concepts were introduced independently in 1948 by James Germain Février (using the term *néosyllabisme*) and David Diringer (using the term *semisyllabary*), and in 1959 by Fred Householder (introducing the term *pseudo-alphabet*).
[src:aslwrite/abugida] The Ethiopic term "abugida" was chosen as a designation for the concept in 1990 by Peter T.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] Faber suggested "segmentally coded syllabically linear phonographic script"; William O.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] Bright used the term *alphasyllabary*; and Gnanadesikan and Rimzhim, Katz, & Fowler suggested *aksara* or *āksharik*.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] Abugidas include the extensive Brahmic family of scripts of Tibet and South and Southeast Asia; Semitic Ethiopic scripts; and Canadian Aboriginal syllabics.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] As in syllabaries, the writing system's units may consist of representations of both syllables and consonants.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] For scripts of the Brahmic family, the term *akshara* is used for the units.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] In several languages of Ethiopia and Eritrea, *abugida* traditionally meant letters of the Ethiopic or Geʽez script in which many of these languages are written.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] The Geʽez script is one of several segmental writing systems; others include Indic/Brahmic scripts and Canadian Aboriginal Syllabics.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] The word *abugida* derives from the letters *'ä, bu, gi,* and *da*, in much the same way that *abecedary* derives from the Latin letters *a be ce de*, *abjad* derives from the Arabic *a b j d*, and *alphabet* derives from the two first letters in the Greek alphabet, *alpha* and *beta*.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] *Abugida* as a term in linguistics was proposed by Peter T.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] Daniels in his 1990 typology of writing systems.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] As Daniels used the word, an abugida contrasts with a syllabary, where letters with shared consonant or vowel sounds have no particular resemblance.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] Furthermore, an abugida contrasts with an alphabet proper, where independent letters denote consonants and vowels.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] The term *alphasyllabary* was suggested for the Indic scripts in 1997 by William O.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] The formal definitions given by Daniels and Bright for abugida and alphasyllabary differ; some writing systems are abugidas but not alphasyllabaries, and some are alphasyllabaries but not abugidas.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] An abugida is defined as "a type of writing system whose basic characters denote consonants followed by a particular vowel, and in which diacritics denote other vowels".
[src:aslwrite/abugida] An alphasyllabary is defined as "a type of writing system in which the vowels are denoted by subsidiary symbols, not all of which occur in a linear order (with relation to the consonant symbols) that is congruent with their temporal order in speech".
[src:aslwrite/abugida] Bright did not require that an alphabet explicitly represent all vowels. ʼPhags-pa is an example of an abugida because it has an inherent vowel, but it is not an alphasyllabary because its vowels are written in linear order.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] The fundamental principles of an abugida apply to words made up of consonant-vowel (CV) syllables.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] The syllables are written as letters in a straight line, where each syllable is either a letter that represents the sound of a consonant and its inherent vowel or a letter modified to indicate the vowel.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] Letters can be modified either by means of diacritics or by changes in the form of the letter itself.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] If all modifications are by diacritics and all diacritics follow the direction of the writing of the letters, the abugida is not an alphasyllabary.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] But most languages have words that are more complicated than a sequence of CV syllables, even ignoring tone.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] The first complication is syllables that consist of just a vowel (V).
[src:aslwrite/abugida] In some languages, a zero consonant letter is used as though every syllable began with a consonant.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] In others, each vowel has a separate letter that is used for each syllable consisting of just the vowel.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] These are known as *independent vowels* and are found in most Indic scripts.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] They may be quite different from the corresponding diacritics, known as *dependent vowels*.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] As a result of the spread of writing systems, independent vowels may be used to represent syllables beginning with a glottal stop, even for non-initial syllables.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] The next two complications are consonant clusters before a vowel (CCV) and syllables ending in a consonant (CVC).
[src:aslwrite/abugida] The simplest solution, which is not always available, is to break with the principle of writing words as a sequence of syllables and use a letter representing just a consonant (C).
[src:aslwrite/abugida] In a true abugida, the lack of distinctive vowel marking of the letter may result from the diachronic loss of the inherent vowel, e.g. by syncope and apocope in Hindi.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] When not separating syllables containing consonant clusters (CCV) into C + CV, these syllables are often written by combining the two consonants.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] In Indic scripts, the earliest method was simply to arrange them vertically, writing the second consonant of the cluster below the first.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] The two consonants may also merge as conjunct consonant letters, where two or more letters are graphically joined in a ligature, or otherwise change their shapes.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] Rarely, one of the consonants may be replaced by a gemination mark, e.g. the Gurmukhi *addak*.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] When arranged vertically, as in Burmese or Khmer, they are said to be "stacked".
[src:aslwrite/abugida] Often there has been a change to writing the two consonants side by side.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] In the latter case, this combination may be indicated by a diacritic on one of the consonants or a change in the form of one of the consonants, e.g. the half forms of Devanagari.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] Generally, the reading order of stacked consonants is top to bottom, or the general reading order of the script, but sometimes the reading order is reversed.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] The division of a word into syllables for the purposes of writing does not always accord with the language's natural phonetics.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] CC or CCVC) are handled by combining the various techniques above.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] Lao and Tāna have dependent vowels and a zero vowel sign, but no inherent vowel.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] Indic scripts originated in India and spread to Southeast Asia, Bangladesh, Sri Lanka, Nepal, Bhutan, Tibet, Mongolia, and Russia.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] All surviving Indic scripts are descendants of the Brahmi alphabet.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] The primary division is between North Indic scripts, used in Northern India, Nepal, Tibet, Bhutan, Mongolia, and Russia, and Southern Indic scripts, used in South India, Sri Lanka and Southeast Asia.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] South Indic letter forms are more rounded than North Indic forms, though Odia, Golmol and Litumol are rounded.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] Most North Indic scripts' full letters incorporate a horizontal line at the top, except in Gujarati and Odia; South Indic scripts do not.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] Indic scripts indicate vowels through dependent vowel signs (diacritics) around the consonants, often including a sign that explicitly indicates the lack of a vowel.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] If a consonant has no vowel sign, this indicates a default vowel.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] Vowel diacritics may appear above, below, to the left of, to the right of, or around the consonant.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] The most widely used Indic script is Devanagari, shared by Hindi, Bihari, Marathi, Konkani, Nepali, and often Sanskrit.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] A basic letter such as क in Hindi represents a syllable with the default vowel, in this case *ka* ([kə]).
[src:aslwrite/abugida] In some languages, including Hindi, it becomes a final closing consonant at the end of a word, in this case *k*.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] The inherent vowel may be changed by adding vowel marks (diacritics), producing syllables such as कि *ki*, कु *ku*, के *ke*, को *ko*.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] In many Brahmic scripts, a syllable beginning with a cluster is treated as a single character for purposes of vowel marking, so a vowel marker like ि *-i,* falling before the character it modifies, may appear several positions before the place where it is pronounced.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] For example, the game cricket in Hindi is क्रिकेट *krikeṭ*; the diacritic for /i/ appears before the consonant cluster /kr/, not before the /r/.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] A more unusual example is seen in the Batak alphabet: the syllable *bim* is written *ba-ma-i-(virama)*.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] That is, the vowel diacritic and virama are both written after the consonants for the whole syllable.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] In many abugidas, there is also a diacritic to suppress the inherent vowel, yielding the bare consonant.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] In Devanagari, प् is *p*, and फ् is *ph*.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] This is called the *virāma* or *halantam* in Sanskrit.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] It may be used to form consonant clusters or to indicate that a consonant occurs at the end of a word.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] Thus in Sanskrit, a default vowel consonant such as फ does not take on a final consonant sound.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] For writing two consonants without a vowel in between, instead of using diacritics on the first consonant to remove its vowel, another common method of special conjunct forms is used in which two or more consonant characters are merged to express a cluster, as in Devanagari's अप्फ *appha*.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] (Some fonts display this as प् followed by फ, rather than forming a conjunct.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] This expedient is used by ISCII and South Asian scripts of Unicode.) Thus a closed syllable such as *phaṣ* requires two *aksharas* to write: फष् *phaṣ*.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] The Róng script used for the Lepcha language goes further than other Indic abugidas, in that a single *akshara* can represent a closed syllable: Not only the vowel but any final consonant is indicated by a diacritic.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] For example, the syllable [sok] would be written as something like s̥̽, here with an underring representing /o/ and an overcross representing the diacritic for final /k/.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] Most other Indic abugidas can indicate only a very limited set of final consonants with diacritics, such as /ŋ/ or /r/, if they can indicate any at all.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] In Geʽez script, *fidels* (individual "letters" of the script) have diacritics that are fused with the consonants to the point that they must be considered modifications of the form of the letters.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] Children learn each modification separately, as in a syllabary; nonetheless, the graphic similarities between syllables with the same consonant are readily apparent, unlike in a true syllabary.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] Though now an abugida, the Geʽez script, until the advent of Christianity (c.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] AD 350), was what would now be termed an *abjad*.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] In the Geʽez script (or *fidel*), the letter's base form (also called *fidel*) may be altered.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] For example, ሀ *hä* [hə] (base form), ሁ *hu* (with a right-side diacritic that does not alter the letter), ሂ *hi* (with a subdiacritic that compresses the consonant, so it is the same height), ህ *hə* [hɨ] or [h] (where the letter is modified with a kink in the left arm).
[src:aslwrite/abugida] In the family known as Canadian Aboriginal syllabics, which was inspired by Devanagari script, vowels are indicated by changing the orientation of the syllabogram.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] Each vowel has a consistent orientation; for example, Inuktitut ᐱ *pi*, ᐳ *pu*, ᐸ *pa*; ᑎ *ti*, ᑐ *tu*, ᑕ *ta*.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] Although a vowel is inherent in each, all rotations have equal status and none can be identified as basic.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] Bare consonants are indicated either by separate diacritics or by superscript versions of the *aksharas*; there is no vowel-killer mark.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] Abjads are typically written without indication of many vowels, but in some contexts, such as teaching materials or scriptures, Arabic and Hebrew are written with full indication of vowels via diacritic marks (*harakat*, *niqqud*), making them effectively alphasyllabaries.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] The Arabic script used for South Azerbaijani generally writes the vowel /æ/ (written as ə in North Azerbaijani) as a diacritic but all other vowels as full letters (like Kurdish and Uyghur).
[src:aslwrite/abugida] This means that when no vowel diacritics are present (most of the time), it technically has an inherent vowel.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] But like the Phagspa and Meroitic scripts, whose status as abugidas is controversial (see below), all other vowels are written in-line.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] Additionally, the practice of explicitly writing all-but-one vowel does not apply to loanwords from Arabic and Persian, so the script does not have an inherent vowel for Arabic and Persian words.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] The inconsistency of its vowel notation makes it difficult to categorize.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] The imperial Mongol script called Phagspa was derived from the Tibetan abugida, but all vowels are written in-line rather than as diacritics.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] However, it retains the features of having an inherent vowel /a/ and having distinct initial vowel letters.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] Pahawh Hmong is a non-segmental script that indicates syllable onsets and rimes, such as consonant clusters and vowels with final consonants.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] Thus it is not segmental and cannot be considered an abugida.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] It superficially resembles an abugida with the roles of consonant and vowel reversed.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] Most syllables are written with two letters in the order rime–onset (typically vowel-consonant) even though they are pronounced as onset-rime (consonant-vowel), rather like the position of the /i/ vowel in Devanagari, which is written before the consonant.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] Pahawh is also unusual in that, while an inherent rime /āu/ (with mid tone) is unwritten, it also has an inherent onset /k/.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] For the syllable /kau/, which requires that one of the inherent sounds be overt, it is /au/ that is written.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] Thus the rime (vowel) is basic to the system.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] Drawing a dividing line between abugidas and other segmental scripts can be difficult.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] For example, the Meroitic script of ancient Sudan does not indicate an inherent *a* (one symbol stood for both *m* and *ma,* for example) and is thus similar to Brahmic family of abugidas.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] But other vowels were indicated with full letters, not diacritics or modification, so the system is essentially an alphabet that does not bother to write the most common vowel.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] Several systems of shorthand use diacritics for vowels, but do not have an inherent vowel, and are thus more similar to Thaana and Kurdish script than to Brahmic scripts.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] The Gabelsberger shorthand system and its derivatives modify the *following* consonant to represent vowels.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] The Pollard script, which was based on shorthand, also uses diacritics for vowels; the placements of the vowel relative to the consonant indicate tone.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] Pitman shorthand uses straight strokes and quarter-circle marks in different orientations as the principal "alphabet" of consonants; vowels are shown as light and heavy dots, dashes, and other marks in one of three possible positions to indicate the various vowel-sounds.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] To increase writing speed, Pitman has rules for "vowel indication" using the positioning or choice of consonant signs so that writing vowel-marks can be dispensed with.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] As the term *alphasyllabary* suggests, abugidas have been considered an intermediate step between alphabets and syllabaries.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] Historically, most abugidas appear to have evolved from abjads (vowelless alphabets).
[src:aslwrite/abugida] They contrast with syllabaries, where there is a distinct symbol for each syllable or consonant-vowel combination, and where these have no systematic similarity to each other, and typically develop directly from logographic scripts.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] Most Indian and Indochinese abugidas appear to have developed from abjads with the Kharoṣṭhī and Brāhmī scripts; the abjad in question is usually considered the Aramaic one, but while the link between Aramaic and Kharosthi is more or less undisputed, this is not so with Brahmi.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] The Kharosthi family does not survive today, but Brahmi's descendants include most of the modern scripts of South and Southeast Asia.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] The Geʽez script derives from a different abjad, the Sabean script of Yemen; the advent of vowels coincided with the introduction or adoption of Christianity about AD 350.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] The Ethiopic script is the elaboration of an abjad.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] The Cree syllabary was invented with full knowledge of the Devanagari system.
[src:aslwrite/abugida] The Meroitic script was developed from Egyptian hieroglyphs, in which various schemes of "group writing" were used to show vowels.
[src:aslwrite/accessible-publishing] Alternative formats that have been developed to aid different people to read include varieties of larger fonts, specialised fonts for certain kinds of reading disabilities, braille, e-books, and automated audiobooks and DAISY digital talking books.
[src:aslwrite/accessible-publishing] Accessible publishing has been made easier through developments in technology such as print on demand (POD), e-book readers, the XML structured data format, the EPUB3 format and the Internet.
[src:aslwrite/accessible-publishing] The aim of accessible publishing is to make reading easier for those who have difficulties doing so.
[src:aslwrite/accessible-publishing] This group includes people who are blind or who have low vision, people with learning disabilities, and people who are learning a second language.
[src:aslwrite/accessible-publishing] Accessible publishing also aims to allow people to read whichever format allows them to read fastest or allows them to absorb the information in a better way.
[src:aslwrite/accessible-publishing] In the twenty-first century, the accessible publishing aim is to make every book available in all formats so that every reader can read with ease and proficiency.
[src:aslwrite/accessible-publishing] Before the 21st century, the publishing industry focused on the production of printed books.
[src:aslwrite/accessible-publishing] The predominant publishing theory, which stressed economy of scale, tended to make only one format of a given book available.
[src:aslwrite/accessible-publishing] In this way they could be mass-produced and made available for the general public.
[src:aslwrite/accessible-publishing] This model did not allow for any other format to be widely available, however.
[src:aslwrite/accessible-publishing] There were a number of developments in technology that increased the accessibility of books.
[src:aslwrite/accessible-publishing] The first of these was the development of the braille writing system by Louis Braille in 1821.
[src:aslwrite/accessible-publishing] Then there was the development of audiobooks which originated from the United States Congress in 1931 and became popularised by advances in recording and the use of voice actors.
[src:aslwrite/accessible-publishing] In 1980, Thorndike Press came into existence as a republisher of large print books.
[src:aslwrite/accessible-publishing] Thorndike bought the rights for large print versions of books from publishers and then republished them in a larger and more accessible format for people with reading difficulties.
[src:aslwrite/accessible-publishing] New portable readers, such as the Victor Reader products and the Plextalk Pocket handle talking books in a wide variety of formats including DAISY Digital Talking Book, MP3, text only, and many others.
[src:aslwrite/accessible-publishing] New technology, such as introduced in the Sony Reader of 2004 and Amazon's Kindle in 2007, provided the ability to alter the size of the font automatically.
[src:aslwrite/accessible-publishing] ReadHowYouWant is another leader in developing this technology.
[src:aslwrite/accessible-publishing] It works in partnership with publishers to make books available in all formats all across the world.
[src:aslwrite/accessible-publishing] This includes specially designed fonts for dyslexia, macular degeneration and line tracking problems.
[src:aslwrite/adinkra-symbols] Adinkra symbols have a decorative function but also represent objects that encapsulate evocative messages conveying traditional wisdom, aspects of life, or the environment.
[src:aslwrite/adinkra-symbols] There are many symbols with distinct meanings, often linked with proverbs.
[src:aslwrite/adinkra-symbols] In the words of philosopher and writer Kwame Anthony Appiah, they were one of the means for "supporting the transmission of a complex and nuanced body of practice and belief".
[src:aslwrite/adinkra-symbols] One oral tradition states that Adinkra symbols were originally created by the Bono people of Gyaman.
[src:aslwrite/adinkra-symbols] The Gyaman king, Nana Kwadwo Agyemang Adinkra, originally created or designed these symbols, naming it after himself.
[src:aslwrite/adinkra-symbols] The Adinkra symbols were largely used on pottery, stools etc. by the people of Gyaman.
[src:aslwrite/adinkra-symbols] Adinkra cloth was worn by the king of Gyaman, and its usage spread from Gyaman to Asante and other Akan kingdoms following its defeat.
[src:aslwrite/adinkra-symbols] It is said that the guild designers who designed this cloth for the Kings were forced to teach the Asantes the craft.
[src:aslwrite/adinkra-symbols] Gyaman king Nana Kwadwo Agyemang Adinkra's first son, Apau, who was said to be well versed in the Adinkra craft, was forced to teach more about Adinkra cloths.
[src:aslwrite/adinkra-symbols] Oral accounts have attested to the fact that Adinkra Apau taught the process to a man named Kwaku Dwaku in a town near Kumasi.
[src:aslwrite/adinkra-symbols] Over time, all Akan people, including the Fante, Akuapem and Akyem, made Adinkra symbols a major part of their culture.
[src:aslwrite/adinkra-symbols] This oral tradition of a Gyaman origin for Adinkra, however, has been directly disproven, as the Gyaman-Asante war in which tradition recounts the Asante learning Adinkra symbols from Gyaman started in 1818 and the campaign ended in 1819.
[src:aslwrite/adinkra-symbols] Two years before this, in 1817, Thomas Bowdich visited Kumasi and had personally seen and written about Adinkra cloth being produced in the Asante capital.
[src:aslwrite/adinkra-symbols] He also brought back from Kumasi a physical example of Adinkra cloth, which is still in the British Museum.
[src:aslwrite/adinkra-symbols] The cloth being named Adinkra is explained by an informant from Asokwa who related to Kojo Arthur that King Adinkra's body was found in a pile of dead people and when it was retrieved, his body was found to be covered in *Ntiamu Ntoma* (stamped cloth).
[src:aslwrite/adinkra-symbols] From then on, *Ntiamu Ntoma* became known as Adinkra cloth.
[src:aslwrite/adinkra-symbols] This suggests that the cloth was known before 1818 and became associated with Adinkra after the war.
[src:aslwrite/adinkra-symbols] In the Asokwa and Ntonso areas, Adinkra cloth is still referred to as *Ntiamu Ntoma*.
[src:aslwrite/adinkra-symbols] There are other hypothesis and oral traditions for the origin of Adinkra cloth and its name, such as it originating in Denkyira, though these have not been disproven they all have their respective issues and the exact origin of Adinkra cloth is not something that is clear.
[src:aslwrite/adinkra-symbols] The oldest surviving adinkra cloth was made in 1817.
[src:aslwrite/adinkra-symbols] The cloth features 15 stamped symbols, including *nsroma* (stars), *dono ntoasuo* (double Dono drums), and diamonds.
[src:aslwrite/adinkra-symbols] The patterns were printed using carved calabash stamps and a vegetable-based dye.
[src:aslwrite/adinkra-symbols] It has resided in the British Museum since 1818, when it was donated by Thomas E.
[src:aslwrite/adinkra-symbols] The next oldest piece of *adinkra* textile was sent in 1825 from Elmina Castle to the royal cabinet of curiosities in The Hague, in response to an assignment from Major Friedrich Last, who was appointed temporary Commander of Dutch Gold Coast.
[src:aslwrite/adinkra-symbols] He probably had the cloth commissioned for William I of the Netherlands, which would explain why the coat of arms of the Netherlands is in the centre.
[src:aslwrite/adinkra-symbols] The other motifs are typical of the older *adinkras*.
[src:aslwrite/adinkra-symbols] It is now on display in the National Museum of Ethnology in Leiden.
[src:aslwrite/adinkra-symbols] In November 2020, a school board in York, Pennsylvania, United States, banned "a children's colouring book that featured African Adrinkra [*sic*] symbols found in fabrics, logos and pottery".
[src:aslwrite/adinkra-symbols] The decision was subsequently overturned.
[src:aslwrite/adinkra-symbols] In Akan (Twi), the term *adinkra* refers not to symbols but to a particular type of cloth.
[src:aslwrite/adinkra-symbols] *Adinkra* cloths were traditionally only worn by royalty and spiritual leaders for funerals and other very special occasions.
[src:aslwrite/adinkra-symbols] In the past, they were hand-printed on undyed, red, dark brown or black hand-woven natural cotton fabric, depending on the occasion and the wearer's role; nowadays they are frequently mass-produced on brighter coloured fabrics.
[src:aslwrite/adinkra-symbols] The present centre of traditional production of *adinkra* cloth is Ghana, Ntɔnso, 20 km northwest of Kumasi and in Ivory Coast.
[src:aslwrite/adinkra-symbols] Dark Adinkra *aduro* pigment for the stamping is made there, by soaking, pulverizing, and boiling the inner bark and roots of the badie tree (*Bridelia ferruginea*) in water over a wood fire.
[src:aslwrite/adinkra-symbols] Once the dark colour is released, the mixture is strained, and then boiled for several more hours until it thickens.
[src:aslwrite/adinkra-symbols] The stamps are carved out of the bottom of a calabash piece.
[src:aslwrite/adinkra-symbols] They measure between five and eight centimetres square.
[src:aslwrite/adinkra-symbols] They have a handle on the back, and the stamp itself is slightly curved so that the dye can be put on with a rocking motion.
[src:aslwrite/adinkra-symbols] Recorded sample of 53 *adinkra* symbols and their meanings.
[src:aslwrite/asl-phabet] Like SignFont and Stokoe notation, ASL-phabet is a phonemic script, but it has been simplified to the point where there is some ambiguity, that is, one symbol can represent more than one phonemic element (handshape, location or movement).
[src:aslwrite/asl-phabet] For example, whereas SignFont has 25 letters encoding types of movement, and Stokoe notation has 24, ASL-phabet has just 5.
[src:aslwrite/asl-phabet] This can result in homographs (more than one sign spelled the same way).
[src:aslwrite/asl-phabet] All together, ASL-phabet has 22 letters for handshape, 5 for location, and 5 for movement.
[src:aslwrite/asl-phabet] They are written in that order, left-to-right, with the possibility for several letters of each type, such as two handshape letters for a two-handed sign.
[src:aslwrite/asl-phabet] Like Stokoe notation (but unlike SignFont), the ASL-phabet does not provide symbols for facial expressions, mouthing, and other aspects of sign language structure, which may make it hard to use for extended text.
[src:aslwrite/asl-phabet] However, it is sufficient to look up ASL words in an ASL–English dictionary.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] Its core components are digits, locatives, marks and movements which are written in a fairly rigid order (though in a fairly flexible configuration) from left to right.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] The order of the writing is from left to right, top to bottom, with locatives or certain marks often beginning words.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] Sentences are ended by the full stop mark ().
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] Questions in written ASL are denoted by eyebrow marks bounding the question not unlike Spanish's "¿ ?." Question words or wh-questions in ASL can also form the interrogative.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] There are in total 105 characters in ASLwrite with 67 digits, five diacritic marks, twelve locatives, sixteen extramanual marks and five movement marks.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] Since its creation, it has evolved to include more digits, locatives, movements and marks as well as modify those already present.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] si5s, a system built from SignWriting, was first proposed by Robert Arnold in his 2007 Gallaudet thesis *A Proposal of the Written System for ASL*.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] The ASLwrite community split from Arnold upon his decision to maintain si5s as a private venture with ASLized after the publication of his and Adrean Clark's book *How to Write American Sign Language*.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] Aside from the small, but dedicated, Facebook group of around 470 in July 2023, ASLwrite is rarely used outside such online spaces.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] However, one of the most popular online ASL dictionaries, HandSpeak, has begun to incorporate ASLwrite as the primary written component of ASL definitions.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] ASLwrite is a somacheirographic system meaning that it represents the body (Greek: σῶμα *sôma* 'body') and hands (Greek: χείρ *kheír* 'hand') and relays phonemic information.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] However, it also incorporates logographs (questioning marks) and is featural.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] The general principle is to capture a single ASL word per segment, from left to right, registering non-manual feature(s), location(s), handshape(s), movement(s) and general orientation.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] It imagines the writer/speaker is looking down at their hands or viewing words from the profile such that words can be made either as if seen from straight-on or from one's profile.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] The digibet captures handshape information as well as orientation, movement and some locations.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] Locatives are characters that capture location, though handshape diacritics like *edge* do capture some locations such as edge of palm.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] Diacritics, such as movements, modify handshapes and can indicate small movements or small orientations.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] Movements themselves are fairly flexible in their shapes and orientations, which makes digitising this script difficult.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] Frontal or profile locatives – Captures the same location information, just from two perspectives.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] An example (seen on the right) is the shoulder locative is either a shoulder frontal locative that is written above or below the handshape(s).
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] Handshapes – Can be written before or after the locative.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] A handshape can be oriented in 360° depending on its location and is written at the end of its movement path if there is one.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] Each handshape present is written, and when more than one handshape (of one hand) is written, a movement must be present.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] Movements – Larger movements or movements that affect multiple handshapes.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] When a handshape changes without overt movement, the handshapes are written left-to-right with a single movement below, similar to an underline.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] Non-manual & punctuation marks – These are questioning marks such as *why*, *who*, *how* and *how*.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] The digibet is composed of handshapes called digits that are modified by diacritics and movements.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] It shares 23 handshapes with ASL's manual alphabet.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] Digits are grouped together by features such as +thumb/-thumb or +closed/-closed.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] In practise, there are 67 digits in ASLwrite's digibet, though that number is growing as new digits are added representing diverse handshapes.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] Moreover, other languages may adopt this system which would add increasingly more digits.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] There are five diacritics, of which one is a movement diacritic.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] Movements are flexible and thus hard to capture in a digital or non-handwritten fashion.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] The movements are diverse and aim to capture the movements of the hands, arms and body.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] There are three points – an **endpoint**, a **firmpoint** and a **contactpoint** –, an **orbit mark**, a **steering** and a **crank mark** as well as the movement mark or line.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] The movement line follows the path of the hand(s) and can be as clean (e.g., – or | ) or as erratic as possible.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] The points denote the end of a handshape's path and the degree to which the motion is made.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] A contactpoint denotes an imaginary or in-the-air point with the contactpoint ending at a location and noted as being a firm ending with the firmpoint.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] The orbit mark indicates a central "point" around which the handshapes orbit; for orbital paths cut short, one would use a steering mark, and for parallel cranking motions, the crank mark would be used.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] The locatives are characters that denote a specific location on or near the signer's body.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] They are presented from a face-on and side-view.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] The two sub-classifications are **frontal** and **profile locatives**.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] Non-manual marks vary quite significantly and can only be placed at the beginning or end of words or phrases.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] **Eyebrow marks** are denoted before and after the word(s) in question thus bounding the words that are modified by eyebrow marks.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] They are called: **Raised (), Knit, Wan, Slanted** and **Squint**.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] Questioning marks exist in ASL as logographs that denote ASL's wh-questions such as WHO or FOR-FOR.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] They are placed after a closed word's or phrase's second eyebrow mark and can exist as an entire sentence alone.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] Mouth marks are characters that relay what action the mouth is doing.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] It is placed inside the first eyebrow mark.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] Body movements are non-manual, non-facial features such as **shoulder shift ()** or **head nod**.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] They, as well as **nose crinkle ()**, stand alone and can be inserted anywhere, inside and outside of eyebrow-marked phrases.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] means *Yes?* in ASL composed of , , and where the raised eyebrow marks at the beginning and the end indicate it is a yes/no question, and the hinge mark () denotes that the S handshape digit () makes a nodding motion.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] The circular point at the end is a full stop mark indicating the end of the sentence.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] Unlike in English writing, the full stop mark () is employed for all sentences, even questions (as seen here).
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] Breaks in the sentence, as seen below, are denoted by the shoulder shift mark ().
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] The text on the right is from Chapters 1:2–4 of the Book of Ruth.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] The first quoted text is the verse in English and the second is an ASL gloss.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] Due to the complexity of the writing system and its need for flexibility for movements, it means that producing anything in a digital format is difficult.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] However, there are efforts to create fonts headed by members of its Facebook group, notably looking at proper font creation and using current keyboard characters such as ' } ' or ' _.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] ' to achieve minor forms of communication in ASL over text.
[src:aslwrite/aslwrite] An example phrase is " }_.U- " which means 'thank you' in ASL.
